#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:5
msgid "Data types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:7
msgid ":ref:`Data type objects <arrays.dtypes>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:10
msgid "Array types and conversions between types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:12
msgid ""
"NumPy supports a much greater variety of numerical types than Python does. "
"This section shows which are available, and how to modify an array's data-"
"type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:15
msgid ""
"NumPy numerical types are instances of `numpy.dtype` (data-type) objects, "
"each having unique characteristics.  Once you have imported NumPy using "
"``import numpy as np`` you can create arrays with a specified dtype using "
"the scalar types in the numpy top-level API, e.g. `numpy.bool`, `numpy."
"float32`, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:20
msgid ""
"These scalar types as arguments to the dtype keyword that many numpy "
"functions or methods accept. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:23
msgid ""
">>> z = np.arange(3, dtype=np.uint8)\n"
">>> z\n"
"array([0, 1, 2], dtype=uint8)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:27
msgid "Array types can also be referred to by character codes, for example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:29
msgid ""
">>> np.array([1, 2, 3], dtype='f')\n"
"array([1.,  2.,  3.], dtype=float32)\n"
">>> np.array([1, 2, 3], dtype='d')\n"
"array([1.,  2.,  3.], dtype=float64)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:34
msgid ""
"See :ref:`arrays.dtypes.constructing` for more information about specifying "
"and constructing data type objects, including how to specify parameters like "
"the byte order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:38
msgid "To determine the type of an array, look at the dtype attribute::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:40
msgid ""
">>> z.dtype\n"
"dtype('uint8')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:43
msgid ""
"dtype objects also contain information about the type, such as its bit-width "
"and its byte-order.  The data type can also be used indirectly to query "
"properties of the type, such as whether it is an integer::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:47
msgid ""
">>> d = np.dtype(np.int64)\n"
">>> d\n"
"dtype('int64')\n"
"\n"
">>> np.issubdtype(d, np.integer)\n"
"True\n"
"\n"
">>> np.issubdtype(d, np.floating)\n"
"False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:57
msgid ""
"To convert the type of an array, use the .astype() method. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:59
msgid ""
">>> z.astype(np.float64)                 \n"
"array([0.,  1.,  2.])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:62
msgid ""
"Note that, above, we could have used the *Python* float object as a dtype "
"instead of `numpy.float64`.  NumPy knows that :class:`int` refers to `numpy."
"int_`, :class:`bool` means `numpy.bool`, that :class:`float` is `numpy."
"float64` and :class:`complex` is `numpy.complex128`.  The other data-types "
"do not have Python equivalents."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:69
msgid ""
"Sometimes the conversion can overflow, for instance when converting a `numpy."
"int64` value 300 to `numpy.int8`. NumPy follows C casting rules, so that "
"value would overflow and become 44 ``(300 - 256)``. If you wish to avoid "
"such overflows, you can specify that the overflow action fail by using "
"``same_value`` for the ``casting`` argument (see also :ref:`overflow-"
"errors`)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:75
msgid ""
">>> z.astype(np.float64, casting=\"same_value\")   \n"
"array([0.,  1.,  2.])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:80
msgid "Numerical Data Types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:82
msgid ""
"There are 5 basic numerical types representing booleans (``bool``), integers "
"(``int``), unsigned integers (``uint``) floating point (``float``) and "
"``complex``. A basic numerical type name combined with a numeric bitsize "
"defines a concrete type.  The bitsize is the number of bits that are needed "
"to represent a single value in memory. For example, `numpy.float64` is a 64 "
"bit floating point data type. Some types, such as `numpy.int_` and `numpy."
"intp`, have differing bitsizes, dependent on the platforms (e.g. 32-bit vs. "
"64-bit CPU architectures).  This should be taken into account when "
"interfacing with low-level code (such as C or Fortran) where the raw memory "
"is addressed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:94
msgid "Data Types for Strings and Bytes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:96
msgid ""
"In addition to numerical types, NumPy also supports storing unicode strings, "
"via the `numpy.str_` dtype (``U`` character code), null-terminated byte "
"sequences via `numpy.bytes_` (``S`` character code), and arbitrary byte "
"sequences, via `numpy.void` (``V`` character code)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:101
msgid ""
"All of the above are *fixed-width* data types. They are parameterized by a "
"width, in either bytes or unicode points, that a single data element in the "
"array must fit inside. This means that storing an array of byte sequences or "
"strings using this dtype requires knowing or calculating the sizes of the "
"longest text or byte sequence in advance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:107
msgid ""
"As an example, we can create an array storing the words ``\"hello\"`` and "
"``\"world!\"``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:110
msgid ""
">>> np.array([\"hello\", \"world!\"])\n"
"array(['hello', 'world!'], dtype='<U6')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:113
msgid ""
"Here the data type is detected as a unicode string that is a maximum of 6 "
"code points long, enough to store both entries without truncation. If we "
"specify a shorter or longer data type, the string is either truncated or "
"zero-padded to fit in the specified width::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:118
msgid ""
">>> np.array([\"hello\", \"world!\"], dtype=\"U5\")\n"
"array(['hello', 'world'], dtype='<U5')\n"
">>> np.array([\"hello\", \"world!\"], dtype=\"U7\")\n"
"array(['hello', 'world!'], dtype='<U7')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:123
msgid ""
"We can see the zero-padding a little more clearly if we use the bytes data "
"type and ask NumPy to print out the bytes in the array buffer::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:126
msgid ""
">>> np.array([\"hello\", \"world\"], dtype=\"S7\").tobytes()\n"
"b'hello\\x00\\x00world\\x00\\x00'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:129
msgid ""
"Each entry is padded with two extra null bytes. Note however that NumPy "
"cannot tell the difference between intentionally stored trailing nulls and "
"padding nulls::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:133
msgid ""
">>> x = [b\"hello\\0\\0\", b\"world\"]\n"
">>> a = np.array(x, dtype=\"S7\")\n"
">>> print(a[0])\n"
"b\"hello\"\n"
">>> a[0] == x[0]\n"
"False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:140
msgid ""
"If you need to store and round-trip any trailing null bytes, you will need "
"to use an unstructured void data type::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:143
msgid ""
">>> a = np.array(x, dtype=\"V7\")\n"
">>> a\n"
"array([b'\\x68\\x65\\x6C\\x6C\\x6F\\x00\\x00', "
"b'\\x77\\x6F\\x72\\x6C\\x64\\x00\\x00'],\n"
"      dtype='|V7')\n"
">>> a[0] == np.void(x[0])\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:150
msgid ""
"Advanced types, not listed above, are explored in section :ref:"
"`structured_arrays`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:156
msgid "Relationship Between NumPy Data Types and C Data Types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:158
msgid ""
"NumPy provides both bit sized type names and names based on the names of C "
"types. Since the definition of C types are platform dependent, this means "
"the explicitly bit sized should be preferred to avoid platform-dependent "
"behavior in programs using NumPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.types.rst:163
msgid ""
"To ease integration with C code, where it is more natural to refer to "
"platform-dependent C types, NumPy also provides type aliases that correspond "
"to the C types for the platform. Some dtypes have trailing underscore to "
"avoid confusion with builtin python type names, such as `numpy.bool_`."
msgstr ""

